ctivism, she examines the transformation of the rural “alphabet school” from an instrument of the civilizing state into a tool of Aymara cultural power, collective representation, and rebel activism. From the metaphorical threshold of the rural school, Larson rethinks the politics of race and indigeneity, nation and empire, in postcolonial Bolivia and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEducationxAims and objectiveszBolivia. 0aEducation-Aims and objectives-Bolivia. 0aIndians of South AmericaxEducationzBoliviaxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous people-Education-Bolivia-History-20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027560?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027560423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027560/original  a978-3-11-131913-1  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2023  aZDB-23-DGGb2023